---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, allPaths, appBySlug, appPairs, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const slug = Astro.params.slug || '';
const path = Array.isArray(slug) ? slug.join('/') : slug;
const parts = path.split('/').filter(Boolean);
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
function channelApps(){ return APPS.filter(a => a.channels.includes(site.channel) || a.channels.includes('marketing')); }
let valid = allPaths().includes(path);
if (!valid) return Astro.redirect('/');
const pairs = appPairs();
const primaryApps = channelApps().slice(0,12);
const operatingNotes = "A Shopify marketing app should be judged by the operating load it creates after the first launch. The attractive demo is not enough. Merchants need clean customer data, useful product context, safe consent handling, clear reporting, and a workflow a small team can repeat every week. The right decision usually comes from mapping the next ninety days: which flow must ship, which segments matter, which offers protect margin, who owns creative, and how revenue quality will be measured after the campaign is live.";
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={`/${path}`}>
  <section class="border-b border-cyan-300/20 bg-[radial-gradient(circle_at_20%_0%,#155e75,transparent_30%),linear-gradient(135deg,#020617,#0f172a_55%,#111827)] py-16">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="badge">{site.primaryKeyword} decision memo</span>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">{title}</h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-4xl text-xl text-slate-300">{desc} This page is written for operators building {site.angle}; it focuses on what to launch, what to measure, where the app can break, and how it should fit into a broader Shopify growth system.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">App roster</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Ranked Shopify marketing app reviews</h2><p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-slate-300">This roster covers lifecycle email, SMS, popups, loyalty, reviews, referrals, analytics, search, upsells, and conversion tools. The ranking favors Shopify data depth, practical implementation, and whether the app helps a merchant operate more intelligently over time.</p></div><div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{APPS.map((app,i)=><a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}><div class="text-sm font-black text-cyan-200">#{i+1} · {app.category}</div><h2 class="mt-3 text-2xl font-black text-white">{app.name}</h2><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-300">Best for {app.bestFor}.</p><p class="mt-4 text-sm font-black text-cyan-100">{app.pricing}</p></a>)}</div></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container grid gap-8 py-14 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_340px]"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>What {app.name} does in a Shopify marketing stack</h2><p>{app.shopifyFit} For searches around <strong>{site.primaryKeyword}</strong>, the central question is not whether {app.name} can send a campaign or install a widget. The real question is whether it can convert Shopify events into better commercial decisions: who should be contacted, what proof or offer should be shown, which product context matters, and when the next message becomes too much.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><h2>Where {app.name} fits best</h2><p>{app.name} is strongest for {app.bestFor}. In a practical stack, that means it should own a clear job rather than sit beside five overlapping tools. A store should define the primary revenue motion before implementation: capture more subscribers, recover carts, educate new buyers, stimulate repeat orders, collect proof, grow loyalty, or explain attribution. Without that job definition, even a strong app becomes another dashboard nobody opens.</p><h2>Strengths that matter</h2><ul>{app.strengths.map(s=><li>{s}</li>)}</ul><p>The strengths above should be tested with live Shopify data. Build a small pilot around one segment and one purchase moment. Look for whether the tool exposes the fields your team actually uses: order count, products purchased, product viewed, discount sensitivity, consent status, location, customer value, subscription status, and recent engagement. A pretty editor is useful, but the data model determines how precise the marketing can become.</p><h2>Limits and failure modes</h2><ul>{app.limits.map(l=><li>{l}</li>)}</ul><p>The common failure mode is buying software before choosing the operating cadence. Marketing apps need owners. Someone must review segments, approve offers, refresh creative, watch deliverability or placement, and compare attributed revenue against total store behavior. If that work is skipped, the app may still report wins, but the merchant will not know whether it created durable profit.</p><h2>Shopify buying advice</h2><p>Choose {app.name} if its workflow depth matches your next ninety days of retention and conversion work. Skip it if the team only needs a one-off newsletter sender, a temporary pop-up, or a dashboard that duplicates reporting already available elsewhere. For {site.keywordPlural}, the winning tool is the one your team will actually operate weekly, learn from monthly, and keep connected to the customer journey as the store changes.</p></article><aside class="card h-fit"><div class="text-sm font-black uppercase tracking-wide text-cyan-200">Snapshot</div><dl class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-sm text-slate-300"><div><dt class="font-black text-white">Category</dt><dd>{app.category}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black text-white">Pricing</dt><dd>{app.pricing}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black text-white">Best for</dt><dd>{app.bestFor}</dd></div></dl><a class="btn btn-primary mt-6 w-full" href="https://sequenzy.com">Compare with Sequenzy</a></aside></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Battlecards</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Side-by-side app comparisons</h2><p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-slate-300">Use these comparison pages to pick by business model, operating workload, and Shopify data depth rather than brand familiarity.</p></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{pairs.map(([a,b])=><a class="card" href={`/compare/${a.slug}-vs-${b.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{a.name} vs {b.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Which is better for {site.primaryKeyword.toLowerCase()}?</p></a>)}</div></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container py-14"><div class="card overflow-x-auto"><table class="data-table"><thead><tr><th>Criteria</th><th>{a?.name}</th><th>{b?.name}</th><th>Shopify takeaway</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Best fit</td><td>{a?.bestFor}</td><td>{b?.bestFor}</td><td>Pick based on operating model, not logo recognition.</td></tr><tr><td>Pricing</td><td>{a?.pricing}</td><td>{b?.pricing}</td><td>Model costs against list growth, message volume, and team time.</td></tr><tr><td>Primary strength</td><td>{a?.strengths[0]}</td><td>{b?.strengths[0]}</td><td>{site.primaryKeyword} should create revenue you can defend.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><article class="prose-shopify mt-8 card"><h2>Verdict for {site.primaryKeyword}</h2><p>{a?.name} is usually better when you need {a?.bestFor}. {b?.name} is stronger when the store cares more about {b?.bestFor}. The right answer depends on the highest-value bottleneck in the store: acquisition capture, checkout recovery, product education, social proof, repeat purchase, loyalty, or analytics.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><p>If both tools look close, run a migration-risk test before committing. Can your team rebuild the top five revenue flows, segment by product and order history, preserve consent, keep creative consistent, and read revenue by campaign without manual spreadsheet work? If the answer is no for one option, the cheaper headline price may become expensive after launch.</p><h2>Implementation sequence</h2><p>Start with the job closest to cash. For most Shopify stores that means welcome capture, abandoned cart, post-purchase education, replenishment, or winback. Launch one flow, measure customer quality, then add the next layer only after reporting is trusted. This disciplined sequence prevents the marketing stack from becoming a noisy collection of automations with no owner.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'for' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Segment maps</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Marketing stacks by store type</h2></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{SEGMENTS.map(s=><a class="card" href={`/for/${s.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{s.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Primary marketing problem: {s.pain}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const seg=SEGMENTS.find(s=>s.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>How {seg.name} should choose {site.primaryKeyword}</h2><p>{seg.name} have to account for {seg.pain}. That changes the app shortlist: the best choice is not always the largest platform, but the one that maps store-specific signals into timely, useful messages. A marketing stack for this segment should make the next customer action obvious without relying on constant discounts.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><h2>Recommended shortlist</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,8).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Implementation notes for {seg.name}</h2><p>Start with one money flow, one trust-building flow, and one reactivation flow. The money flow addresses the nearest purchase event: welcome, cart recovery, replenishment, or repeat order. The trust flow answers the reason a customer hesitates: proof, education, sizing, ingredients, quality, timing, or service. The reactivation flow protects the customer file from going cold by using purchase timing and category interest instead of blasting every lapsed buyer with the same coupon.</p><p>For {site.keywordPlural}, more campaigns are not automatically better. Better timing and cleaner segmentation usually beat extra sends. This is especially true when {seg.pain} affects the buying cycle. A merchant should document what data the app needs, what content must be created, and what metric will prove the flow deserves to remain live.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Play library</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Use cases for the full marketing stack</h2></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{USE_CASES.map(u=><a class="card" href={`/use-cases/${u.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{u.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Use {site.primaryKeyword.toLowerCase()} to {u.job}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Best approach for {u.name}</h2><p>The job of {u.name} is to {u.job}. For {site.primaryKeyword}, that means using Shopify events, product context, consent, and customer history to decide who gets the message and when. A strong play should feel like a continuation of the shopping experience, not a disconnected blast from a marketing calendar.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><h2>Apps to consider</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,8).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a>: {a.shopifyFit}</li>)}</ul><h2>What to measure</h2><p>Measure recovered revenue, repeat purchase rate, margin after discounts, unsubscribe or opt-out pressure, customer support issues, and revenue by segment. Avoid judging {u.name} only by opens, clicks, or platform-attributed revenue. The better question is whether the play changes the customer journey in a way that the store can keep funding.</p><h2>Launch checklist</h2><p>Before launch, define the trigger, exclusion rules, offer logic, creative promise, suppression window, and owner. After launch, review examples of real customers entering and exiting the flow. This small manual audit often catches problems dashboards miss: expired products, awkward timing, discount overlap, or a message that makes sense to marketers but not to shoppers.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'alternatives' && (() => { const app=appBySlug((parts[1]||'').replace('-alternative',''))!; const alts=APPS.filter(a=>a.slug!==app.slug).slice(0,8); return <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Why Shopify stores look for {app.name} alternatives</h2><p>{app.name} is a credible option, but it is not always the right fit for every store searching for {site.primaryKeyword}. Common reasons to compare alternatives include pricing, channel mix, migration workload, segmentation depth, reporting confidence, team preference, and how much Shopify-specific context the app exposes inside daily workflows.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><h2>Best alternatives</h2><ul>{alts.map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Selection rule</h2><p>Do not switch tools just for a cleaner interface. Switch when the alternative makes an important Shopify workflow easier to launch, easier to measure, or cheaper to scale. The safest migration begins with a single flow or widget, proves that reporting matches store reality, and only then moves the rest of the lifecycle program.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'guides' && <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Shopify marketing app selection framework</h2><p>Pick {site.primaryKeyword} by matching your business model to lifecycle jobs. New stores need capture, welcome, cart recovery, proof, and first purchase campaigns. Growing stores need segmentation, post-purchase education, replenishment, loyalty, winback, and deliverability discipline. Larger brands need governance, experimentation, attribution, creative operations, and channel coordination.</p><p>{operatingNotes}</p><p>A practical audit starts with the customer journey, not the app store. Write down the moments where money leaks: anonymous visitors leave, subscribers never buy, carts stall, new customers get anxious, repeat purchase timing is missed, VIP buyers receive generic offers, reviews are not reused, and reporting cannot explain incrementality. Then choose tools that close the most expensive leaks first.</p><h2>Internal linking map</h2><ul><li><a class="link" href="/apps">All apps</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/compare">Comparison battlecards</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart guide</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/for/fashion">Fashion store guide</a></li></ul></article></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app=appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Deep stack role for {app.name}</h2><p>A serious Shopify marketing app review has to define the job {app.name} owns inside the stack. The app might capture demand, recover hesitation, automate lifecycle email, coordinate SMS, collect reviews, power loyalty, improve merchandising, or explain performance. The mistake is treating every app as a general growth tool. A store that installs overlapping tools without a clear owner for each customer moment usually creates more dashboards, more scripts, and less accountability.</p><p>Evaluate {app.name} against the next ninety days of Shopify work. The first week should prove clean installation, data flow, consent handling, theme impact, and whether the team can operate the app without developer help. The second week should launch one revenue moment. The third week should connect reporting to Shopify order quality. The fourth week should remove friction, suppress irrelevant audiences, and decide whether the app deserves a larger role.</p><p>The best apps turn store context into action. They know which product a shopper viewed, which collection created intent, which discount a customer used, how many times the customer purchased, whether the item is replenishable, whether a review request is appropriate, and whether another channel has already contacted the person. If {app.name} cannot use that context, it may still be useful, but it should be scoped narrowly.</p><p>Team workload matters as much as features. Someone must own creative, offers, segments, performance review, and QA. If the app makes those jobs obvious, it can compound. If it requires constant manual exports, duplicate rule building, or fragile theme edits, the hidden cost may exceed the subscription. A practical Shopify stack should make the merchant faster and more precise, not more dependent on emergency fixes.</p><p>Choose {app.name} when its strengths match the store’s immediate bottleneck and its limits do not create new operational debt. Skip it when the team cannot name the specific flow, widget, segment, or report it will improve in the first month. Marketing apps should earn shelf space by changing customer behavior, not by promising every possible channel at once.</p></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b]=parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Expanded {a?.name} vs {b?.name} stack comparison</h2><p>Compare {a?.name} and {b?.name} by assigning each one a specific Shopify growth job. One may be better for lifecycle campaigns, another for proof, another for loyalty, another for capture, and another for analytics. A meaningful comparison asks which customer moment is currently leaking money and which app can fix that moment with the least operating drag.</p><p>Build the same pilot in both tools. Define the trigger, audience, creative, offer, destination, reporting view, suppression rule, and owner. If the tool touches the theme, check speed and placement. If it sends messages, check consent and frequency. If it claims attribution, compare platform revenue to Shopify orders and margin. The winner should be clearer after a workflow test than after a feature matrix.</p><p>Pricing should include subscription cost, usage cost, agency cost, developer cost, and the cost of mistakes. A cheaper app that needs manual cleanup can become expensive; a more powerful app that nobody operates can become shelfware. Model the next traffic spike, catalog expansion, or sale period before deciding either option is affordable.</p><p>Data depth is often the decisive factor. Shopify marketing works when product, order, customer, discount, review, loyalty, and engagement context move together. If one app cannot see the fields that matter for the store’s buying cycle, it should lose points even if it looks polished. The goal is not a beautiful dashboard; the goal is better customer decisions.</p><p>Choose the app that improves habits. A good stack has weekly review, creative refreshes, offer discipline, QA, and clear ownership. The wrong app adds another place to check without changing behavior. The right app makes the next growth action easier to see and safer to execute.</p></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const seg=SEGMENTS.find(s=>s.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Long-form marketing stack plan for {seg.name}</h2><p>{seg.name} need a marketing stack shaped around {seg.pain}. That means the store should not copy a generic app list. It should map the customer journey from first visit to repeat purchase, then identify where the current experience leaks attention, trust, or margin. The right apps make those leaks measurable and easier to fix.</p><p>Start with capture and intent. Visitors may arrive through paid social, search, influencers, email, referrals, or seasonal demand. The stack should remember what brought them in and what product or collection created interest. That context should influence popups, email, SMS, product recommendations, reviews, loyalty prompts, and retargeting audiences. Without shared context, each app behaves like a separate marketer with a partial memory.</p><p>Next build trust and conversion assets. For this segment, shoppers may need education, sizing, proof, ingredient clarity, financing, delivery expectations, gifting support, or reassurance after checkout. Reviews, UGC, lifecycle messages, merchandising, and support links should work together. A marketing app is valuable when it moves those assets into the customer moment where they matter most.</p><p>Retention should be designed before the first sale ends. Post-purchase education, replenishment, loyalty, winback, and VIP treatment all depend on order history. The app stack should help the merchant decide who should hear from the brand, which channel should carry the message, and when silence is better than another promotion. More automation is not automatically better; better timing usually wins.</p><p>For {seg.name}, choose apps that reduce operational confusion. The team should know who owns each tool, what metric proves value, and what weekly review keeps it healthy. If an app adds another script, another dashboard, and another conflicting offer without a clear customer benefit, it does not belong in the stack.</p></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Full-stack execution plan for {u.name}</h2><p>The job of {u.name} is to {u.job}, but a Shopify marketing stack should decide which app and channel should perform each part of the job. Sometimes the answer is email. Sometimes it is SMS, onsite merchandising, reviews, loyalty, a popup, a product recommendation, or a cleaner analytics view. The play works when those layers share context rather than fighting for credit.</p><p>Define the trigger first. What behavior proves the customer is ready for the play? A visit, product view, cart, checkout, purchase, review, loyalty milestone, subscription event, or lapsed window all mean different things. Then define exclusions. Recent buyers, open support issues, gift purchasers, discount-sensitive segments, and VIP customers may need separate handling.</p><p>Creative should match the customer’s reason to hesitate. A high-intent visitor may need proof and urgency. A new customer may need confidence and education. A lapsed buyer may need relevance, not just a coupon. A VIP may need access before a public sale. The app stack should make those distinctions practical without requiring a custom project for every message.</p><p>Measurement must go beyond attributed revenue. Track margin after incentives, conversion by segment, repeat purchase behavior, unsubscribes or opt-outs, site speed impact, support tickets, and whether the play reduces paid acquisition pressure. A play that earns revenue while creating confusion or over-discounting is not durable.</p><p>Choose Shopify marketing apps for {u.name} by asking which platform makes the next improvement easiest. The strongest stack lets a small team inspect real customers, adjust rules, update creative, and understand results without exporting half the store. If the tools cannot support that loop, the use case will stay shallow.</p></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'alternatives' && (() => { const app=appBySlug((parts[1]||'').replace('-alternative',''))!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Migration plan for {app.name} alternatives</h2><p>Searching for {app.name} alternatives should begin with a clear failure diagnosis. The store may need lower cost, better Shopify data, faster setup, stronger lifecycle guidance, cleaner reporting, fewer theme conflicts, or a tool that fits the team’s workflow. Each reason leads to a different shortlist. Switching because the interface feels stale is not enough.</p><p>Document every asset before moving: forms, automations, widgets, reviews, loyalty rules, discount codes, segments, suppression lists, attribution settings, theme placements, scripts, and reports. Decide which assets deserve to survive. Many migrations are successful because they delete clutter, not because the new app magically fixes strategy.</p><p>Protect data continuity. Contacts, consent, order history, product context, review status, loyalty points, tags, and engagement events may all influence future marketing. If the alternative cannot preserve or reconstruct that context, the store risks sending less relevant campaigns after the move. Test with real customer examples before full migration.</p><p>Move in stages. Rebuild one high-value workflow or widget, compare it with {app.name}, and verify that reporting matches Shopify reality. Then expand. This staged approach prevents the team from discovering problems during a sale, launch, or seasonal spike.</p><p>The best alternative should leave the store with a clearer operating rhythm: fewer overlapping tools, better ownership, more reliable data, and a stronger link between customer behavior and marketing action. If the replacement only changes the dashboard while leaving the same workflow confusion, keep looking.</p></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b]=parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Final stack governance notes for {a?.name} and {b?.name}</h2><p>Before selecting either app, define governance. Who approves the offer, who checks theme impact, who owns segmentation, who reads the report, and who decides when the play should be paused? Shopify marketing apps often fail because the tool is installed but ownership is vague. The better option between {a?.name} and {b?.name} is the one that supports a clear owner and a repeatable review habit.</p><p>Run a failure rehearsal as well. Imagine the app slows a key template, sends a stale product, duplicates a discount, misreads attribution, or conflicts with another tool. Which platform makes the issue easier to detect and unwind? A marketing stack is only as strong as its weakest operational handoff. Choose the app that makes those handoffs visible.</p><p>Finally, compare the apps against the next campaign calendar. A tool that works during a quiet week may break down during a product launch, holiday promotion, influencer spike, or inventory constraint. The stronger choice helps the team coordinate creative, segments, offers, and reporting when the store is under pressure.</p><p>That pressure test matters because Shopify teams rarely evaluate software in calm conditions. They need tools that keep rules understandable when merchandising, retention, paid media, support, and leadership all need answers at once, especially during revenue-critical weeks when vague ownership becomes expensive.</p></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Governance checklist for {u.name}</h2><p>Before launch, assign one owner for the play and one metric that decides whether it stays live. If the use case touches multiple tools, document the handoff: onsite capture to email, email to SMS, review request to UGC, loyalty status to segmentation, or analytics back to campaign planning. These handoffs are where generic stacks break down.</p><p>After launch, review real customer paths rather than only aggregate reports. Check whether the right people entered, whether excluded customers stayed out, whether the offer preserved margin, whether the destination matched the promise, and whether support received avoidable questions. A mature Shopify marketing stack improves through this small weekly inspection cycle.</p><p>If the play keeps underperforming, change one variable at a time: audience, timing, proof, offer, destination, or channel. This keeps learning clean and prevents the team from blaming the app when the strategy is unclear. Durable growth comes from controlled iteration, not constant tool switching.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app=appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>{app.name} stack worksheet: role, rollout, and failure modes</h2><p>Evaluate {app.name} by assigning it one precise job in the Shopify stack. It might capture demand, recover checkout hesitation, automate lifecycle messaging, coordinate SMS, collect proof, improve loyalty, power merchandising, or clarify analytics. The tool should lose points if it overlaps with existing apps without making ownership simpler. A merchant needs to know which customer moment {app.name} owns, what data it consumes, what surface it changes, and which metric proves it deserves to stay installed.</p><p>Run a four-week rollout instead of a broad install. Week one checks data flow, consent, theme impact, customer identity, product feed accuracy, and whether scripts slow important templates. Week two launches one commercial play with exclusions and an owner. Week three compares platform reporting with Shopify orders, margin, and customer support signals. Week four either expands the app's role or trims it back. This prevents a shiny app from becoming a permanent tax on speed.</p><p>Migration and implementation risks include duplicate discounts, mismatched audience definitions, broken product recommendations, review widgets that hurt load time, loyalty rules nobody can explain, analytics that over-credit campaigns, and email or SMS offers that conflict with onsite banners. Before relying on {app.name}, test real customers and edge cases: recent purchasers, VIPs, gift buyers, high-AOV browsers, subscription customers, and lapsed shoppers.</p><h3>Score {app.name}</h3><ul><li><strong>Role clarity:</strong> one primary job and a named owner.</li><li><strong>Data depth:</strong> useful access to Shopify product, order, customer, consent, review, and loyalty signals.</li><li><strong>Operational safety:</strong> QA, suppression, theme impact, and rollback paths are visible.</li><li><strong>Measurement:</strong> reporting ties to margin, repeat behavior, and customer quality rather than dashboard credit alone.</li></ul></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b]=parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Expanded stack scorecard for {a?.name} vs {b?.name}</h2><p>Compare the apps by assigning each one the same Shopify growth scenario: capture a visitor, recover a cart, educate after purchase, collect proof, trigger a repeat purchase, and report whether the play created quality revenue. Document the trigger, audience, creative, offer, destination, Shopify data fields, suppression rule, owner, and reporting view. The better app is the one that makes the customer path and operating owner clearer.</p><p>{a?.name} should win if it solves the most expensive leak with less stack friction. {b?.name} should win if it connects better to the store's next quarter: launch planning, retention, reviews, loyalty, merchandising, analytics, or channel coordination. A generic winner is less useful than a role-specific winner. The question is not which app is famous; it is which one improves the next customer decision.</p><p>Model cost beyond subscription. Include usage fees, agency work, developer time, theme performance, duplicate scripts, discount leakage, reporting cleanup, and the cost of mistakes during a sale. Then rehearse failure: a widget slows a product page, an offer conflicts with email, an attribution report over-credits a campaign, or a product feed recommends unavailable items. Choose the app that makes detection and repair easier.</p><h3>Decision rubric</h3><ul><li>Which app has the clearer stack role?</li><li>Which app needs fewer manual exports or duplicate segments?</li><li>Which app protects margin and customer trust during busy campaigns?</li><li>Which app will the team actually review and improve every week?</li></ul></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Full build sheet for {u.name}</h2><p>Build {u.name} as a cross-stack play, not a single automation. Decide which layer creates the trigger, which layer carries the message, which layer supplies proof, which layer owns the offer, and which layer measures the outcome. For abandoned cart, that may mean onsite reassurance, email proof, SMS urgency, discount control, and analytics. For replenishment, it may mean product usage logic, lifecycle email, SMS only near the decision window, loyalty context, and post-purchase education.</p><p>Define exclusions before creative. Recent purchasers, support issues, gift buyers, VIPs, subscription customers, refunded orders, and discount-only shoppers can all distort results if they enter the same path. The marketing stack should make those rules visible across tools. If one app sends a coupon while another asks for a review or pushes a different offer, the customer sees confusion even if each dashboard looks correct.</p><p>Measure the play against commercial quality. Track margin after incentives, conversion by segment, repeat purchase movement, opt-outs or unsubscribes, support tickets, site speed impact, and whether paid acquisition dependence falls. Pull real customer journeys during the first month. A play can look successful in aggregate while sending awkward messages to high-value customers.</p><h3>Mistakes to avoid</h3><ul><li>Letting multiple apps claim ownership of the same customer moment.</li><li>Launching {u.name} without a suppression window and rollback plan.</li><li>Judging the play only by attributed revenue or clicks.</li><li>Adding a new app when a clearer segment, offer, or proof asset would fix the problem.</li></ul></article></section> })()}

