  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Operator evidence to collect before trusting {app.name}</h2><p>This {site.primaryKeyword} review should leave a growth lead with evidence, not vibes. Open Shopify and choose five real customer timelines: a new subscriber with no orders, a shopper who abandoned a high-value product, a recent first-time buyer, a repeat buyer who normally purchases on a predictable cycle, and a lapsed customer who once bought during a sale. Then test whether {app.name} can explain what each person should receive next and what they should be excluded from. If the answer depends on a spreadsheet, hidden tag, or agency-only convention, the app is weaker than the demo suggests.</p><p>For this site, the important surface area is capture, email, SMS, reviews, loyalty, merchandising, analytics, onsite proof, and campaign governance. {app.name} earns a stronger score when those jobs live in one understandable operating rhythm. It loses points when it creates a prettier editor but leaves trigger accuracy, consent, product context, suppression, or reporting ambiguous. The practical question is whether a merchant can make a safe change on a busy Thursday before a launch without breaking another journey.</p><p>Ask the vendor to walk through a failure. Inventory is out of stock, a coupon is already attached, a customer purchased on another device, deliverability softened last week, and a campaign is scheduled for the same audience tomorrow. A serious marketing app makes the safe answer visible. A shallow tool still sends because the automation technically qualifies.</p><h3>Evidence checklist</h3><ul><li>Real Shopify customer examples match the intended journeys and exclusions.</li><li>Product, order, consent, discount, and customer-stage fields are visible where the marketer edits the workflow.</li><li>The team can name the owner, review cadence, rollback path, and metric that decides whether the workflow stays live.</li><li>Reporting connects to incremental revenue, app cost, speed to launch, repeat behavior, margin, support load, and whether a named owner can run the workflow rather than only platform-attributed revenue.</li></ul></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Deeper buying test for {a?.name} vs {b?.name}</h2><p>A useful comparison should simulate the next ninety days, not just compare menus. Build the same operating calendar in both tools: one acquisition capture path, one intent-recovery path, one customer education path, one repeat-purchase or reactivation path, and one high-pressure promotion. For each, document the trigger, audience, exclusion, offer, product context, channel coordination, reporting view, and owner. The winner is the tool that makes the calendar easier to run after the onboarding call ends.</p><p>Use {site.primaryKeyword} criteria instead of generic SaaS criteria. The deciding work is capture, email, SMS, reviews, loyalty, merchandising, analytics, onsite proof, and campaign governance. If {a?.name} handles those jobs with fewer manual rules, it deserves the nod even if {b?.name} has a nicer campaign editor. If {b?.name} protects adding another dashboard that overlaps existing tools without improving ownership better, that matters more than one extra dashboard. Shopify teams do not need abstract power; they need safe changes, cleaner targeting, and revenue that survives margin math.</p><p>Do not let attribution settle the argument by itself. Compare the tools against incremental revenue, app cost, speed to launch, repeat behavior, margin, support load, and whether a named owner can run the workflow. Also count team time: setup meetings, QA passes, segment cleanup, creative edits, agency dependency, support tickets, and the cost of fixing mistakes. A cheaper app can become expensive if every sale week requires manual audits. A powerful app can become expensive if nobody trusts the interface enough to keep improving flows.</p><h3>Decision notes to write down</h3><ul><li>Where {a?.name} is clearly safer or faster.</li><li>Where {b?.name} is clearly safer or faster.</li><li>Which customer moment is most valuable for this store right now.</li><li>What migration step would break revenue if rushed.</li></ul></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const useCase = USE_CASES.find((item) => item.slug === parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Advanced implementation notes for {useCase.name}</h2><p>{useCase.name} should start with a policy, not a template. Write the commercial rule first: who qualifies, why the message is useful now, what product or order context changes the copy, when the customer should be suppressed, and which other campaigns take priority. Then choose the marketing app that can express that policy without a tangle of manual tags.</p><p>For {site.primaryKeyword}, the hidden work is capture, email, SMS, reviews, loyalty, merchandising, analytics, onsite proof, and campaign governance. A thin setup sends the same message to every eligible profile. A stronger setup changes timing and proof based on the customer: first-time versus repeat buyer, full-price versus coupon buyer, high-AOV versus low-margin cart, subscription versus one-off order, gift purchase versus self purchase, and recent support issue versus clean journey. These differences are where the revenue quality comes from.</p><p>Before launch, run a QA table with at least ten examples. Include recent purchasers, inactive subscribers, VIPs, discount-sensitive shoppers, customers with multiple carts, buyers whose product is out of stock, and people already scheduled for a campaign. Record the expected outcome and the actual outcome. If the app cannot explain a mismatch, fix the rule before sending. After launch, review incremental revenue, app cost, speed to launch, repeat behavior, margin, support load, and whether a named owner can run the workflow and one or two customer timelines each week until the workflow behaves predictably.</p><h3>Common pitfalls</h3><ul><li>Launching {useCase.name} with a clever subject line but weak exclusions.</li><li>Letting attributed revenue hide adding another dashboard that overlaps existing tools without improving ownership.</li><li>Using one offer for every customer value band.</li><li>Failing to pause or adjust the workflow during launches, stockouts, holidays, and support spikes.</li></ul></article></section> })()}


