    <section class="container pb-16">
      <article class="prose-shopify card">
        <h2>Field notes before putting this page into the shortlist</h2>
        <p>This page should be read with a real Shopify account open beside it. The best way to use the advice is to choose one current customer moment, pull the actual Shopify fields behind it, and decide whether the tool or workflow can make a safer decision than the store makes today. For this domain, the repeated buying pressure is stack ownership, app overlap, campaign governance, customer data quality, and margin-aware reporting. If a page does not help the growth owner make those decisions more clearly, it is only keyword coverage.</p>
        <p>Write down the current baseline before changing anything: how many customers qualify, what percent are recent purchasers, which products or collections are involved, what offer is attached, how often the audience overlaps with campaigns, and what revenue Shopify shows without platform attribution. Then model the improved version. A stronger setup should reduce ambiguity: fewer customers in the wrong audience, cleaner product context, safer discounts, better timing, and a review loop that a non-technical operator can repeat.</p>
        <p>The migration note matters because Shopify retention systems usually fail at the edges. Consent timestamps disappear, old tags keep firing, product blocks show stale inventory, coupons stack, segment counts shift, and reporting changes make the new tool look better or worse than it really is. Keep the first rollout narrow enough that the team can inspect individual customer timelines. If the tool cannot explain why ten sample customers did or did not qualify, it is not ready for a broad launch.</p>
        <p>Finally, judge the page by whether it protects against dashboard sprawl, script bloat, and offers that conflict across channels. A tool can create attributed revenue while making the program less disciplined. A better choice should make restraint easier: suppress when the customer already bought, hold back when margin is weak, pause during stockouts, branch when lifecycle stage changes, and measure the behavior that continues after the campaign. That is the standard behind the recommendations here.</p>
